diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.description: Kawasaki disease is a rare condition that mainly affects children under the age of 5. It's characterized by inflammation of blood vessels throughout the body and can lead to coronary artery aneurysms. Key features include fever, conjunctivitis, swollen and red hands and feet, rash, and red, cracked lips.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Stevens-Johnson syndrome is a rare, serious disorder of the skin and mucous membranes. It's usually a reaction to a medication or an infection. Symptoms may include flu-like symptoms, followed by a painful red or purplish rash that spreads and blisters, conjunctivitis, and erythema multiforme.

diagnoses.name: Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS) Syndrome
diagnoses.description: DRESS syndrome is a drug-induced condition characterized by extensive rash, fever, lymphadenopathy, hematologic abnormalities, and internal organ involvement. Skin manifestations may include erythema multiforme.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis
diagnoses.description: Toxic epidermal necrolysis is a life-threatening skin disorder characterized by widespread erythema, necrosis, and bullous detachment of the epidermis and mucous membranes, resulting in exfoliation and possibly sepsis and/or death. It is often drug-induced.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet Fever
diagnoses.description: Scarlet fever is a bacterial illness that develops in some people who have strep throat. It's characterized by a bright red rash on the body, usually accompanied by high fever and sore throat. Additional symptoms can include redness in the folds of the skin and a strawberry-tongue appearance.

diagnoses.name: Acute Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.description: Acute rheumatic fever is a disease that can affect the heart, joints, skin, and brain. It's caused by an autoimmune response to a streptococcal infection. Symptoms can include fever, painful and tender joints, rash, and uncontrolled movements (Sydenham chorea).

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: Dermatomyositis is an inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash. It's considered a muscular dystrophy that affects adults and children. Skin changes may include a rash on the face, knuckles, neck, shoulders, upper chest, and back.

diagnoses.name: Graft versus Host Disease
diagnoses.description: Graft versus host disease (GVHD) is a condition that occurs when donor bone marrow or stem cells attack the recipient. Symptoms can include skin rash, liver dysfunction, and gastrointestinal symptoms. Skin manifestations might resemble erythema multiforme.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: Lyme disease is an infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. Early symptoms may include fever, headache, and fatigue. A characteristic skin rash called erythema migrans is commonly observed. However, the additional symptoms listed are less typical for Lyme disease.

diagnoses.name: Erythema Infectiosum (Fifth Disease)
diagnoses.description: Erythema infectiosum, also known as Fifth Disease, is a viral infection causing a mild rash illness that affects mostly children. It's characterized by a 'slapped cheek' rash on the face and sometimes a lacy red rash on the body and limbs. However, the specific combination of symptoms provided is not typical.

diagnoses.name: Neurosyphilis
diagnoses.description: Neurosyphilis can cause a variety of symptoms including seizures and mental disturbances along with skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: SLE is an autoimmune disease that can affect the skin, causing rashes and dyspigmentation, and the nervous system, potentially leading to seizures and psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Secondary Syphilis
diagnoses.description: Secondary syphilis can present with skin rashes including maculopapular and psoriasiform rashes, and in later stages can affect the brain.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: HIV can cause a variety of skin manifestations including maculopapular rash and may lead to neurological complications resulting in seizures or psychosis, especially in advanced stages.

diagnoses.name: Pellagra
diagnoses.description: Caused by niacin (Vitamin B3) deficiency, pellagra leads to dermatitis, diarrhea, and dementia, which can include seizures and psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: Late-stage Lyme disease can cause neurological symptoms, including psychosis and seizures, and skin manifestations such as a rash.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: Sarcoidosis is an inflammatory disease that can cause a wide range of symptoms, including skin rashes and neurological effects like seizures and psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Tuberous Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that causes growths in multiple organs, including the skin, brain (leading to seizures), and can present with various skin abnormalities.

diagnoses.name: Drug Reactions
diagnoses.description: Adverse reactions to drugs can cause a range of symptoms, including psoriasiform rashes, dyspigmentation, seizures, and in rare cases, psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Psoriasis
diagnoses.description: While primarily a skin condition, psoriasis can have systemic involvement and, in rare cases, may be associated with seizures due to neuroinflammation.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder characterized by dry eyes and dry mouth. It can also lead to fatigue, joint pain, and has been associated with conditions such as POTS and chronic pain.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory and mood issues. It often coexists with other painful conditions like chronic back pain and endometriosis.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (CFS)
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. Cognitive dysfunction and post-exertional malaise are common. It can co-occur with POTS and chronic pain conditions.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. It's often associated with POTS, chronic pain, and cognitive dysfunction.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. It can cause symptoms like fatigue, pain, cognitive dysfunction, and may have a relationship with other autoimmune conditions.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune condition that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs. Symptoms can include fatigue, joint pain, rash, and inflammation affecting other systems.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that can affect more than just your joints. In some people, the condition can damage a wide variety of body systems, including the skin, eyes, lungs, heart, and blood vessels.

diagnoses.name: Interstitial Cystitis
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition causing bladder pressure, bladder pain, and sometimes pelvic pain. The condition is a part of the spectrum of diseases known as painful bladder syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS)
diagnoses.description: An intestinal disorder causing pain in the belly, gas, diarrhea, and constipation. It's a chronic condition that you'll need to manage long term and can have an impact on quality of life.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.description: Although primarily known as a mental health condition, depression can significantly affect physical health and well-being, contributing to chronic pain, fatigue, and making other symptoms feel worse.

diagnoses: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) exacerbation with bronchitis

Autoimmune Thyroid Disease (Hashimoto’s thyroiditis) – Can present with hypothyroidism and, in some cases, may be associated with immune-mediated hyperglycemia.
Graves’ Disease – While primarily associated with hyperthyroidism, it can cause episodic weakness and is an autoimmune disorder, which may lead to various hypersensitivity reactions.
Lymphoma – Lymphadenitis could be a symptom; lymphomas can also cause systemic symptoms including episodic weakness and metabolic disturbances.
Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE) – Autoimmune disease that could explain hypothyroidism, hypersensitivity reactions, and lymphadenitis.
Mononucleosis (Infectious or EBV-associated) – Could cause lymphadenitis, and in some cases, autoimmune phenomena including hypothyroidism.
Thyroiditis - Subacute or silent thyroiditis can cause hypothyroidism and might be associated with systemic immune responses like hypersensitivity reactions.
Multiple Sclerosis – Could explain episodic weakness and, though less common, can be associated with autoimmune thyroid disorders.
Adrenal Insufficiency (Addison’s Disease) – Can cause hypoglycemia primarily but in cases of autoimmune polyglandular syndrome, may present with hypothyroidism and episodes of weakness.
Type 2 Diabetes with Diabetic Polyneuropathy – While the primary feature is hyperglycemia, poorly controlled diabetes can lead to episodic weakness due to neuropathy.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.reasoning: PCOS can cause the formation of cysts, along with hormonal imbalances that might lead to symptoms like abnormal liver enzymes due to its associated metabolic syndromes. Hyperthyroidism has been observed in some patients with PCOS, although the connection is complex.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Thyroid Disease (such as Graves' Disease)
diagnoses.reasoning: Graves' Disease can cause hyperthyroidism. Autoimmune conditions can sometimes affect multiple organ systems leading to a variety of symptoms, including liver enzyme abnormalities.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Hepatitis
diagnoses.reasoning: Chronic hepatitis can lead to abnormal liver enzymes and, in some cases, can be associated with extrahepatic symptoms such as thyroid dysfunction.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.reasoning: HIV/AIDS can lead to a multitude of symptoms including vaginitis due to its effect on the immune system. The virus can also impact the liver, leading to abnormal enzyme levels, and affect thyroid function indirectly.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.reasoning: Diabetes can cause cyst formation (such as in cases of cystic complications in organs), impact liver function leading to abnormal liver enzymes, and potentially correlate with thyroid dysfunctions due to hormonal imbalances. Vaginitis can be more common in diabetic patients due to the increased risk of infections.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: This systemic autoimmune disease can affect various glands and tissues, leading to symptoms like dryness (which might contribute to sinusitis) and potentially impact the liver and thyroid. The connection to cysts and vaginitis is less direct but could be considered in the context of systemic involvement and secondary effects.

diagnoses.name: Lupus (Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, SLE)
diagnoses.reasoning: Lupus can affect multiple organ systems including the thyroid and liver, possibly leading to the observed symptoms. The relationship with cysts and vaginitis can stem from overall inflammation and immune system dysregulation.

diagnoses.name: Thyroiditis
diagnoses.reasoning: Thyroiditis encompasses a group of disorders that cause inflammation of the thyroid, which can lead to hyperthyroidism. Secondary effects might include impacts on the liver enzymes. The connection to the other symptoms would need further investigation.

diagnoses.name: Gonorrhea
diagnoses.reasoning: This sexually transmitted disease can directly cause vaginitis and potentially involve complications or spread that might secondarily affect other body systems, including impacts on the liver. The ties to cysts, hyperthyroidism, and sinusitis would be more indirect, focusing on systemic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Chlamydia
diagnoses.reasoning: Similar to Gonorrhea, Chlamydia can cause vaginitis and could potentially have broader systemic effects, including on the liver. The connection to the other symptoms would likely be indirect, possibly related to inflammation or secondary complications.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Contact Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: A skin condition that occurs when an individual comes into contact with a substance that triggers an allergic reaction, causing symptoms like dyshidrotic eczema and hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland is underactive and produces insufficient hormones, potentially leading to symptoms such as constipation and hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS)
diagnoses.description: A disorder affecting the large intestine, causing symptoms like constipation. Although not directly linked to skin or periodontal health, systemic manifestations can include a variety of hypersensitivity responses.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic disorder characterized by sudden and severe episodes of swelling (angioedema), which can be triggered by hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands responsible for keeping the eyes, mouth, and other parts of the body moist and lubricated, potentially leading to periodontal disease among its wide array of symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, causing systemic hypersensitivity reactions. It can be associated with a broad spectrum of conditions, including dermatological and gastrointestinal symptoms like constipation.

diagnoses.name: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD)
diagnoses.description: A term primarily referring to Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis, which are characterized by chronic inflammation of the gastrointestinal tract, potentially causing constipation and systemic manifestations including skin and hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Lactose Intolerance
diagnoses.description: The inability to fully digest lactose, leading to gastrointestinal symptoms like constipation when dairy products are consumed. Though primarily affecting digestive health, it can precipitate broader hypersensitivity reactions in the body.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Urticaria
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by the development of hives and angioedema for more than six weeks, often triggered by hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Psoriasis
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune skin condition that speeds up the life cycle of skin cells, causing scales and red patches. It can also manifest with systemic symptoms, including joint problems and, in some cases, hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Peptic Ulcer Disease
diagnoses.description: An open sore that develops on the inside lining of the stomach and the upper portion of the small intestine. Symptoms include stomach pain, bloating, and heartburn.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension (High Blood Pressure)
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the force of the blood against the artery walls is too high. Usually asymptomatic, but can lead to significant health issues like heart disease and stroke.

diagnoses.name: Gastric Cancer
diagnoses.description: A disease in which malignant (cancer) cells form in the lining of the stomach. Symptoms may include indigestion or stomach discomfort, a bloated feeling after eating, mild nausea, and loss of appetite.

diagnoses.name: Oral Cancer
diagnoses.description: Cancer that occurs in the oral cavity. Leukoplakia can be a precursor to oral cancer. Symptoms may include sores, lumps or rough spots in the mouth, as well as difficulty chewing or swallowing.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that affect how your body uses blood sugar (glucose). Sensory neuropathies are a common complication. Symptoms of diabetes include increased thirst, frequent urination, hunger, fatigue, and blurred vision.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition where stomach acid frequently flows back into the tube connecting your mouth and stomach (esophagus). This can lead to symptoms like heartburn.

diagnoses.name: Peripheral Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A result of damage to your peripheral nerves, often causing weakness, numbness, and pain, usually in your hands and feet. It can be associated with a variety of conditions, including diabetes.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: This condition occurs when the body does not have enough vitamin B12, causing tiredness, weakness, constipation, loss of appetite, weight loss, and neuropathy.

diagnoses.name: Esophageal Cancer
diagnoses.description: Cancer of the esophagus has symptoms including difficulty swallowing, weight loss, chest pain, worsening indigestion or heartburn, and coughing or hoarseness.

diagnoses.name: Helicobacter pylori Infection
diagnoses.description: A type of bacteria that infects the stomach. It is a common cause of peptic ulcers and can lead to stomach pain, nausea, and bloating.

diagnoses.name: Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by a significant increase in heart rate upon standing, often accompanied by symptoms like lightheadedness, fainting, and rapid heartbeat. It might coexist with other systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to overproduce red blood cells, which can lead to thickened blood, and may present with symptoms like headache, dizziness, and exhaustion. Pallor might not be a direct symptom but could relate to complications or concurrent conditions.

diagnoses.name: Primary Hyperparathyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by overactivity of one or more of the parathyroid glands, leading to increased calcium levels in the blood, which can cause bone loss (osteoporosis), kidney stones, and joint pain.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that primarily affects joints causing pain and swelling but can also cause systemic symptoms including osteoporosis, and in rarer cases, may be associated with conditions like POTS.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body, including skin, joints, kidneys, heart, lungs, blood vessels, and the brain. It can cause joint pain, and in more severe cases, lead to complications such as osteoporosis.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: Condition in which the kidneys lose function over time. It can be linked to high blood pressure, which can contribute to the development of polycythemia and can cause complications leading to osteoporosis and pallor.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Myeloma
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that affects plasma cells and can cause bone pain and osteoporosis. It might be associated with anemia, leading to pallor, rather than directly with polycythemia.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition that causes pain all over the body, fatigue, and other symptoms. It's not directly linked to polycythemia or osteoporosis but can coexist with conditions like POTS.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland is underactive and doesn't produce enough thyroid hormone, leading to symptoms such as joint pain, and in severe cases, can be associated with high cholesterol levels which may contribute to polycythemia.

diagnoses.name: Osteogenesis Imperfecta
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder characterized by bones that break easily, often with little or no apparent cause. It directly causes osteoporosis and joint pain, but it's less commonly associated with polycythemia or POTS.

diagnoses.name: Common Variable Immune Deficiency (CVID)
diagnoses.description: CVID is a disorder characterized by low levels of several immunoglobulin classes, leading to a decreased ability to fight infections. Patients may experience recurrent infections such as bronchitis, lung infections, and gastrointestinal infections. Fibrosis can occur as a complication from chronic infections.

diagnoses.name: Hyper IgM Syndromes
diagnoses.description: These syndromes are a group of rare genetic disorders leading to defective class-switch recombination, resulting in high levels of IgM and low levels of other immunoglobulins. Patients typically present with recurrent infections, including bronchitis and pneumonia, which can lead to lung damage and fibrosis.

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia Gravis
diagnoses.description: Myasthenia Gravis is an autoimmune neuromuscular disorder characterized by muscle weakness that worsens after periods of activity and improves after periods of rest. It does not directly cause decreased immunoglobulins, bronchitis, or fibrosis, but patients can have a generalized decreased immune function.

diagnoses.name: Graves' Disease
diagnoses.description: Graves' disease is an autoimmune disorder leading to overactivity of the thyroid gland (hyperthyroidism). Symptoms include muscle weakness and hyperactivity. It doesn't typically cause decreased immunoglobulins, bronchitis, or fibrosis, but autoimmune conditions can coexist.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: COPD is a chronic inflammatory lung disease that causes obstructed airflow from the lungs. Symptoms include breathing difficulty, cough, mucus (sputum) production, and wheezing. It includes chronic bronchitis and emphysema and can lead to lung fibrosis.

diagnoses.name: Cystic Fibrosis
diagnoses.description: Cystic fibrosis is a genetic disorder that affects the lungs, pancreas, and other organs. It causes severe damage to the respiratory system, leading to chronic infections and fibrosis. Immune system abnormalities can occur, along with other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Selective IgA Deficiency
diagnoses.description: This is the most common primary immunodeficiency and is characterized by an isolated decrease of IgA. Individuals may suffer from recurrent infections, including bronchitis. It's less associated with systemic fibrosis or episodic weakness.

diagnoses.name: Lambert-Eaton Myasthenic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: This is a rare autoimmune disorder characterized by muscle weakness of the limbs. It is associated with a form of lung cancer in about half the cases, potentially leading to bronchitis and lung fibrosis.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic Pulmonary Fibrosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic and ultimately fatal disease characterized by a progressive decline in lung function due to fibrosis of the lung tissue. It doesn't inherently involve episodic weakness or hyperactivity but can coexist with systemic diseases that affect the immune system.

diagnoses.name: Good's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Rare immunodeficiency associated with thymoma, characterized by low B-cells, hypogammaglobulinemia, and often opportunistic infections. It may present with bronchitis and can lead to pulmonary fibrosis due to recurrent infections.

diagnoses: Inflammatory bowel disease (Crohn’s disease and ulcerative colitis)

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to make too many red blood cells. These excess cells thicken the blood, slowing its flow, and can cause complications such as blood clots. Telangiectasias may appear due to increased blood volume and pressure.

diagnoses.name: Cushing's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A hormonal disorder caused by high levels of cortisol in the blood for a long time. Common symptoms include increased appetite, weight gain, and skin changes like folliculitis. Insomnia can also occur.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia (HHT)
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that affects blood vessels and can cause iron deficiency and, in rare cases, may be associated with elevated red blood cell counts if significant bleeding and subsequent iron supplementation occur.

diagnoses.name: Obstructive Sleep Apnea
diagnoses.description: A condition in which breathing repeatedly stops and starts during sleep. Symptoms can include increased appetite and insomnia. Polycythemia can occur as a complication due to the body producing more red blood cells to compensate for the low oxygen levels.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland is overactive and produces too much thyroid hormone. This can increase metabolism, leading to symptoms such as increased appetite and insomnia. Skin changes such as folliculitis may occur.

diagnoses.name: Carcinoid Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition in which a carcinoid tumor secretes certain chemicals into the bloodstream, leading to symptoms like flushing and telangiectasias. Although polycythemia is not a direct symptom, the systemic effects of the syndrome could potentially influence red blood cell counts indirectly.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory lung disease that causes obstructed airflow from the lungs. Patients may develop polycythemia as a compensatory response to chronic hypoxia. Insomnia and increased appetite can be associated symptoms due to medication side effects or the stress of chronic illness.

diagnoses.name: Pheochromocytoma
diagnoses.description: A rare tumor of the adrenal gland tissue. It may cause high blood pressure, which can lead to symptoms of increased appetite and insomnia. Skin conditions such as folliculitis can also occur due to hormonal imbalances.

diagnoses.name: Rosacea
diagnoses.description: A chronic skin condition that causes redness and visible blood vessels in your face (telangiectasias). While it primarily affects the skin, associated conditions like digestive issues can sometimes affect appetite.

diagnoses.name: Acromegaly
diagnoses.description: A disorder that results from excess growth hormone (GH) after the growth plates have closed. The condition can cause an increased appetite and skin changes, including folliculitis. Insomnia can be a symptom due to discomfort or hormone imbalances.

diagnoses.name: Primary Osteoporosis
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by a decrease in the density of bone, decreasing its strength and resulting in fragile bones, leading to bone fractures. It mainly arises due to a lack of bone tissue without specific identifiable causes, potentially related to aging and reduced levels of hormones, especially in postmenopausal women.

diagnoses.name: Secondary Osteoporosis
diagnoses.description: Osteoporosis that occurs as a result of another medical condition, medication, or lifestyle factor that specifically causes bone loss. This includes conditions or treatments related to hormone imbalances, other diseases, or specific drugs inducing bone density reduction.

diagnoses.name: Peptic Ulcer Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition in which open sores develop on the inside lining of your stomach and the upper portion of your small intestine. The most common symptoms include stomach pain, including ulcers caused or exacerbated by drugs or conditions altering the stomach's environment.

diagnoses.name: Primary Autonomic Failure
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by failure of the autonomic nervous system, which can result in blood pressure lability among other symptoms. This condition represents a failure in the regulation of involuntary functions by the nervous system.

diagnoses.name: Multiple System Atrophy
diagnoses.description: A rare, progressive neurodegenerative disorder characterized by a combination of symptoms that affect both the autonomic nervous system (which controls involuntary actions) and movement. Symptoms include blood pressure lability, and potential olfactory deficits.

diagnoses.name: Hyperparathyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which one or more of the parathyroid glands produces too much parathyroid hormone, leading to elevated levels of calcium in the blood which can result in bone loss, leading to conditions such as osteopenia and osteoporosis, and potentially contributing to ulcer formation.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin D Deficiency
diagnoses.description: Insufficient vitamin D in the body can lead to inadequate calcium absorption from the diet, contributing to the development of osteopenia and osteoporosis, due to decreased bone mineral density and increased bone fragility.

diagnoses.name: Cushing's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A hormonal disorder caused by prolonged exposure to high levels of cortisol. It can lead to a variety of symptoms including an increased risk of osteoporosis/osteopenia due to bone tissue loss, and also potentially increasing ulcer risk.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where stomach contents come back up into the esophagus resulting in either symptoms or complications. It can exacerbate or be confused with symptoms of ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by a gradual loss of kidney function over time. It can lead to disturbances in electrolytes, bone density loss, and contribute to cardiovascular instability including blood pressure lability.

diagnoses: Rhinitis Medicamentosa (Rebound Congestion from Overuse of Nasal Sprays)
Toxic reactions (such as from plants or animal stings)

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, life-threatening allergic reaction that can lead to symptoms such as hives, rhinorrhea (runny nose), and syncope (fainting). Conjunctival injection (red eyes) and potentially incontinence due to loss of muscle control during a severe reaction might also be seen.

diagnoses.name: Vasovagal syncope
diagnoses.description: A common cause of fainting that can be triggered by prolonged standing or emotional distress. It might be accompanied by incontinence due to the temporary loss of consciousness and control. Rhinorrhea or hives could be ancillary symptoms related to the stress or allergies respectively.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Shock Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening complication of certain bacterial infections. It can cause symptoms such as syncope, rash (similar to hives), and incontinence. Rhinorrhea and conjunctival injection are less common but possible depending on the body's reaction.

diagnoses.name: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome (MCAS)
diagnoses.description: A condition where mast cells inappropriately release chemical signals into the bloodstream, leading to a variety of symptoms including hives, syncope, and potentially rhinorrhea and conjunctival injection.

diagnoses.name: Allergic reaction
diagnoses.description: A response of the body to a particular allergen. This can manifest in symptoms such as hives, conjunctival injection, and rhinorrhea. Syncope and incontinence may occur in severe reactions.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that results in recurrent attacks of severe swelling. The episodes can lead to abdominal cramping, difficulty breathing, and potentially hives. Though less common, syncope can occur due to airway obstruction or severe pain.

diagnoses.name: Pheochromocytoma
diagnoses.description: A rare tumor of the adrenal gland tissue. It causes the glands to produce excess catecholamines, leading to symptoms such as hypertension, headache, potential syncope, and in some cases, skin reactions such as hives.

diagnoses.name: Neurocardiogenic syncope
diagnoses.description: A condition that leads to fainting due to a drop in heart rate and blood pressure. While it primarily causes syncope, stress associated with the condition can exacerbate allergic symptoms such as hives, rhinorrhea, and conjunctival injections.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, leading to a wide range of symptoms including rashes (similar to hives), joint pain, and kidney dysfunction. Neurological manifestations might include syncope.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome/Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis
diagnoses.description: A rare, severe disorder of the skin and mucous membranes, often in reaction to a medication or infection. It can feature widespread skin pain, red or purplish skin that looks burned and peels off, as well as mucosal involvement that could explain conjunctival injections and rhinorrhea.

diagnoses: Allergic rhinitis (including pollen, food, medication allergies contributing to nasal congestion)
Acute bacterial sinusitis (secondary to initial viral upper respiratory symptoms, with rare presentations)
Viral upper respiratory infection (with atypical severe reaction)
Addisonian crisis (acute adrenal insufficiency with possible GI symptoms, hypotension)
Inflammatory Bowel Disease (Crohn's disease and Ulcerative Colitis)

diagnoses.name: Allergic Rhinitis
diagnoses.description: An allergy-related condition that occurs when your body's immune system overreacts to substances in the environment, leading to nasal congestion, sneezing, and rhinorrhea.

diagnoses.name: Food Allergy
diagnoses.description: An adverse immune response to certain kinds of food. Symptoms can range from mild, such as hives, to severe, such as anaphylaxis. Abdominal cramps may also occur.

diagnoses.name: Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS)
diagnoses.description: A disorder that affects the large intestine, causing symptoms like abdominal pain, cramping, bloating, and changes in bowel habits. Some individuals might experience incontinence.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction that can occur rapidly. Symptoms include hives, abdominal cramps, and difficulty breathing.

diagnoses.name: Urinary Tract Infection (UTI)
diagnoses.description: An infection in any part of the urinary system, kidneys, bladder, or urethra. It can cause incontinence and abdominal cramping in some cases.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Idiopathic Urticaria
diagnoses.description: A condition where hives occur without a known cause. Symptoms include red, raised itchy bumps on the skin. It may be associated with other symptoms like abdominal cramps.

diagnoses.name: Non-Celiac Gluten Sensitivity
diagnoses.description: A condition where individuals experience symptoms similar to those of celiac disease, such as abdominal cramps, after consuming gluten but do not test positive for celiac disease.

diagnoses.name: Influenza
diagnoses.description: A viral infection that attacks your respiratory system. It can cause a wide range of symptoms, including sneezing, rhinorrhea, and in some cases, abdominal pain.

diagnoses.name: Gastroenteritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the stomach and intestines, typically resulting from a bacterial or viral infection. Symptoms can include abdominal cramps, nausea, and in some cases, incontinence.

diagnoses.name: Stress Response
diagnoses.description: Stress can trigger various physiological reactions in the body, such as sneezing, hives, abdominal cramps, incontinence, and a runny nose due to increased levels of stress hormones.

diagnoses: Common cold (viral upper respiratory tract infection)

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic, typically progressive disease involving damage to the sheaths of nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, symptoms may include numbness, impairment of speech and of muscular coordination, blurred vision and severe fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Any intracranial tumor created by abnormal and uncontrolled cell division, normally either in the brain itself (neurons, glial cells), in the cranial nerves, in the brain envelopes, skull, pituitary, and pineal gland.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition in which poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death, leading to partial or complete loss of function in affected areas. Symptoms can include difficulty with movement, speech, and vision.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by recurrent attacks of severe pain often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound. Visual disturbances or auras may precede the headache.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from a temporary shortage of blood flow to the posterior portion of the brain, causing symptoms like vertigo, dizziness, ataxia, and visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. In most cases, Meniere's disease affects only one ear and can cause a feeling of pressure alongside hearing problems.

diagnoses.name: Arnold-Chiari Malformation
diagnoses.description: A condition in which brain tissue extends into the spinal canal, present at birth. Symptoms can include headaches, difficulty swallowing (sometimes accompanied by gagging), dizziness, nausea, and problems with coordination and balance.

diagnoses.name: Intoxication
diagnoses.description: Poisoning by drugs or alcohol. Symptoms can vary widely but may include ataxia, visual disturbances, nausea, and altered mental status among others.

diagnoses.name: Neurological Infections
diagnoses.description: Infections that affect the nervous system, such as meningitis, encephalitis, or brain abscess. These can cause a wide range of symptoms including fever, headache, confusion, nausea, and problems with movement including ataxia.

diagnoses.name: Acute Disseminated Encephalomyelitis (ADEM)
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disease that rapidly progresses, marked by a sudden, widespread attack of inflammation in the brain and spinal cord, typically after an infection or vaccination. Symptoms can include ataxia, weakness, visual disturbances, and altered mental status.

diagnoses: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (Crohn's disease and Ulcerative Colitis)
Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS)
Hepatitis B or C with Cryoglobulinemia
Hepatitis B or C with Cryoglobulinemia
Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (GPA, formerly Wegener's Granulomatosis)
Autoimmune Hemolytic Anemia with Immune Thrombocytopenia (Evan's Syndrome variant)
Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (GPA, formerly known as Wegener's granulomatosis)
Primary angiitis of the central nervous system

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease characterized by inflammation of various parts of the body. It can manifest with skin rashes, arthritis, kidney problems, and blood disorders such as hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that primarily affects joints but can also cause systemic issues, including skin symptoms and anemia.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands responsible for keeping the eyes, mouth, and other parts of the body moist. It can be associated with other immune system disorders such as rheumatoid arthritis and lupus.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune rheumatic disease characterized by hardening and tightening of the skin and connective tissues. It can also affect internal organs, including the digestive tract and blood vessels.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and skin rash. It is considered an autoimmune disorder and can also present with systemic manifestations, including lung involvement and anemia.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa
diagnoses.description: A serious blood vessel disease characterized by inflammation of small and medium-sized arteries in the body, leading to organ damage and, in some cases, skin manifestations and anemia.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout the body. Symptoms may include mouth sores, genital sores, eye inflammation, and skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (Wegener's)
diagnoses.description: An uncommon disorder that causes inflammation of the blood vessels in your nose, sinuses, throat, lungs, and kidneys. Early symptoms include sinusitis and nasal ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that can affect any organ, leading to a wide range of symptoms, including skin changes, anemia, and arthritis.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disorder that has the features of three other connective tissue diseases: lupus, scleroderma, and polymyositis. It can include symptoms such as joint pain, skin manifestations, and vascular problems.

diagnoses: Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms (DRESS) syndrome
Magic Syndrome (Mouth And Genital Ulcers with Inflamed Cartilage Syndrome)
